<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="149" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="20.[702,1295,302,721]" lastBlockId="20.[89,1295,727,1628]" pageId="20" pageNumber="149">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[703,964,648,681]" pageId="20" pageNumber="149">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 14-1 cm, tail 7-2 cm; weight 70 g. Dorsal and head fur of Pine’s Opossum is uniformly brownish to pale sepia, with no dorsal stripes, no reddish or yellowish color on body sides, and no mid-rostral stripe or eye-rings. Tail length is ¢.51% of head-body length, and tail has fur on its proximal 5 mm at most. Naked rest oftail is pale fuscous dorsally, with fine whitish hairs on ventral surface. Ventral fur is creamy buff, with no mid-ventral cream or whitish stripe, and there is a small patch of gray-based hairs on abdominal region. Fur is 3-4 mm and velvety. Feet are pale buffy and silver. Female Pine’s Opossums probably lack a pouch, as do all other short-tailed opossums, but the only known specimen is a male, and therefore there is no information on number of mammae. Karyotype of Pine’s Opossum is unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="149" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="20.[89,1295,727,1628]" pageId="20" pageNumber="149">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[90,201,1126,1155]" pageId="20" pageNumber="149">Habitat.</emphasis>
Lowland (356 m) humid mixed forest with cane thickets (based on only one specimen).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
